Massive China quake in southwest province
2013-04-20 01:52:12 GMT
A 7.0-magnitude earthquake has hit China in the southwest province of Sichuan.The extent of damages, and casualties if any, remains unclear.The quake struck 115 km southwest of Chengdu, one of the biggest cities in Sichuan province, at 8 am on Saturday, local time.Reuters reports it was centered 69 miles northwest of the town of Leshan. It occurred at a depth of only 10.2 miles below the surface.The quake was felt 71 miles away from the epicenter, in the provincial capital of Chengdu, according to BBC News.A magnitude 8.0 earthquake hit Sichuan in 2008 and killed more than 60,000 people. The quake sparked anger across China when it was revealed that many of the dead were children who died in collapsed schoolbuildings built by corrupt contractors.The quake left millions homeless and could be felt as far away as Shanghai, where it swayed buildings.
